 the backdrop of exhaustion to withhold the promise of reproductive futurity. She explores how adventure stories like Treasure Island and Heart of Darkness reorient fictional space toward the resource frontier. And she shows how utopian and fantasy works like “Sultana’s Dream,” The Time Machine, and The Hobbit offer imaginative ways of envisioning energy beyond extractivism.This illuminating book reveals how an era marked by violent mineral resource rushes gave rise to literary forms and genres that extend extractivism as a mode of environmental understanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIndustrialization in literature. 0aMines and mineral resources in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 19th Century .2bisacsh  aAllan Quatermain.  aArthur Rimbaud.  aAuthor.  aBarbarism (linguistics).  aBildungsroman.  aBloemfontein.  aBoiler.  aBook review.  aBritish Coal.  aCapitalism.  aCase study.  aClimate change.  aCoal mining.  aCoal.  aCommodity.  aConsolidated Mines.  aCrainquebille.  aD. H. Lawrence.  aDeath drive.  aDividend.  aDuPont.  aEcocriticism.  aEcological imperialism.  aEcology.  aEnergy crisis.  aEnvironmental politics.  aEnvironmentalism.  aExhaustion.  aExternality.  aFertilizer.  aFilth (novel).  aFinance capitalism.  aFossil fuel.  aFuel.  aGenre.  aGeologist.  aGeopolitics.  aGeorge Eliot.  aH. G. Wells.  aH. Rider Haggard.  aHartley Colliery disaster.  aHistorical fiction.  aHistoricism.  aImagines (work by Philostratus).  aImperialism.  aInception.  aIndustrial ecology.  aIndustrial society.  aInternational Commission on Stratigraphy.  aJoseph Conrad.  aKing Solomon's Mines.  a